SIMPLE: speculate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Speculate
<hw>Spec"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Speculated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Speculating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>speculatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>speculari</ets> to spy out,
observe, fr. <ets>specula</ets> a lookout, fr. <ets>specere</ets> to
look. See <er>Spy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To consider by turning a
subject in the mind, and viewing it in its different aspects and
relations; to meditate; to contemplate; to theorize; <as>as, to
<ex>speculate</ex> on questions in religion; to <ex>speculate</ex> on
political events.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is remarkable that persons who <qex>speculate</qex> the most
boldly often conform with the most pefect quietude to the external
regulations of society.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Philos.)</fld> <def>To view subjects from certain
premises given or assumed, and infer conclusions respecting them <xex>a
priori</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>To purchase with the expectation
of a contingent advance in value, and a consequent sale at a profit; --
often, in a somewhat depreciative sense, of unsound or hazardous
transactions; <as>as, to <ex>speculate</ex> in coffee, in sugar, or in
bank stock</as>.</def> <-- (finance) -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speculate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Speculate
<hw>Spec"u*late</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To consider attentively;
<as>as, to <ex>speculate</ex> the nature of a thing</as>.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir W. Hamilton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speculation</ent>⟦br⟧
